================================================================================
 Deposit Calculator — isolated debug: core service vs. custom service call
================================================================================
Status: three rounds of guarding testRates (inline !, ??, splitting into a
raw+defaulted assign) have all failed identically at ${testRates?size} —
INSIDE guards that should make that expression impossible to fail. That's
stopped being consistent with a null-handling bug. New leading theory:

  Liferay's Fragment FTL execution runs through a more restricted/sandboxed
  configuration than an ADT does, and that sandbox may only allow reflection
  into WHITELISTED (core Liferay) service interfaces and bean types. A
  custom Service Builder interface like InterestRateUploadLocalService may
  simply not be reachable from Fragment FTL at all on this instance — and
  Liferay's generic error handling reports "evaluated to null or missing"
  for that restriction instead of a clearer permission-denied message.
  ??/! can't fix this: they only rescue an actual null value, not a call
  that the sandbox refuses to make in the first place.

This file adds the one test that tells us definitively which it is: the
exact same serviceLocator pattern, but against a service interface that is
guaranteed to be core/whitelisted (UserLocalService, requesting nothing but
a plain int user count via themeDisplay.getCompanyId() — no custom domain
object involved at all).

  - If the core-service block below renders a real number, and the custom
    block still fails the same way it always has → confirms the sandbox/
    allowlist theory. The fix at that point is NOT more FTL guarding; it's
    going back to a REST Builder or @JSONWebService resource (sections 2/6
    of `calculator`) so the custom entity data reaches the fragment through
    a channel that isn't restricted this way, since that's server code
    running as a trusted OSGi component rather than through Fragment FTL.

  - If the core-service block ALSO fails the same way → serviceLocator
    itself isn't functional in this execution context at all (regardless of
    core vs. custom), which points back at the still-unconfirmed Draft
    preview vs. published-page distinction, or a portal-wide FreeMarker
    restricted-variables setting disabling serviceLocator for Fragments
    entirely on this instance.

Also relevant to the "it is not getting published" symptom: that means
Liferay is running this FTL through a validation/compile pass at PUBLISH
time itself, not only at page-render time — so whatever's failing here is
failing before a real request/session context necessarily even exists,
which is itself a point in favor of the sandbox-restriction theory over a
data-dependent null.

